===from:Dallas Crowley
===email:kcrowley@nwiowa.com
===institution:Albert City-Truesdale Community School
===date:Sat Jan 17  9:16:49 1998
===subject:Key to aging
===message:If this is the same chemical, we're talking about a protein that is the core of the enzyme called human telomerase.  And yes, when this enzyme gets overambitious we do end up with cancer as Kim suggested.  It is also related to reverse transcriptase which is the viral enzyme that lets HIV "steal" human cells.  So essentially what allows HIV to replicate has now been found to be an essential aspect of human cell development.

Telomerase helps young, dividing cells by rebuilding the tips of chromosomes, called telomeres (thus telomerase).  Once cells are mature, this function is shut off, but is turned back on again in cancer and there is a similar chemical with a similar function in HIV.  Without telomerase, telomeres shrink and break down and eventually die.

To me, the more important aspect of this chemical is not in providing society with eternal youth (with the dangerous side effects already mentioned by Kim and Ross and Jay), but in the increased knowledge it provides us about cancer and HIV.  Perhaps with this new knowledge we can develop a way to turn off the telomerase and reverse transcriptase in cells that have been hijacked by cancer or HIV.
=========yorg=========
