===message:In the messages, I've noticed a theme of concern about overpopulation if this chemical truly can extend life and become commercially available.  Perhaps my message is a blanket response.  Should we ban  research into curing cancer and AIDs because the cures would extend people's lives and contribute to overpopulation?  Should we ban organ transplants because they allow people to live longer and contribute to overpopulation?  Should we ban penicillin and other drugs that help people live longer?I have a sister who successfully fought breast cancer.  I have an uncle who is still alive because of a kidney transplant.  I would have hated to have someone tell me that we aren't going to do anything for them because the world may become overpopulated.  I'm sure each of you has a relative/friend whose life was extended through advances in science.Is this any different?  If I have the opportunity to extend the lives of my loved ones, shouldn't that be the decision of my family?  I don't want to be the one to tell my father/mother/sibling/child that we can't do anything for him/her because there is a famine someplace in Africa.  Are there potential problems?  Absolutely!  But I have faith in man's ability to overcome problems and make this a better place to live.  All I have to do is look at how much better we live today than our ancesters 1,000 years ago or even 100 years ago.
