===from:Bill Rockey
===email:brockey@iastate.edu
===date:Wed Jan 28 19:48:00 1998
===subject:Practical Applications
===message:One practical application of telomerase which the pharmaceutical industry can reap the benefits of in the very near future is the production of "immortal" genetically engineered cell lines to produce products such as human insulin.  Such cell lines would increase the production of pharmaceuticals (lowering their cost in the process) since aging cell lines whose telomeres are nearly gone would not have to be recultured periodically. <P>

In addition, the results of this experiment confirm scientists' theories of cellular mechanics.  Since the function of telomerase is to rebuild the telomere structure of the chromosome after it has been "worn away" through repeated divisions, the insertion of a gene into cells which causes telomerase to be produced and getting the results these scientists did is pretty conclusive proof for the theory that telomeres control cellular aging. <P>

I researched this study on the Web and found a more detailed article than the Register's at http://www.thestate.com/daily/nation/aging14.htm
=========yorg=========
