===message:	The possibility of eternal life has been a quest for man to chase throughout history.  There were worthy quests such as Ponce de Leon’s journey to Florida in 1513, looking for the fountain of youth and Russian reports during the  cold war claimed that some Ukrainians lived abnormally long lives. If these reports were true, the only hope for a longer life was a to possesses the Ukranian’s  special genes. However, scientists have recently found the true way to a longer life.  A new drug takes advantage of replenishing our biological clock by replacing the telomerases on the end of chromosome. Now it comes to society to decide what to do with the knowledge we possesses.  The problem is a fast moving one, with medicine for a longer life only 5-10yrs in the future. One must make a careful and educated decision on whether or not to take this drug. <P>

	Our generation is first seeing the major benefits of genetics and the possibility of a longer life is certainly one of the most profound to date. Genetics has  changed societies resilience to new  and shocking ideas. Within a year, a sheep has been cloned, a Chicago scientist is ready to clone humans, and now a life elongating drug has been announced. I wonder how long before society feels the need to backlash and slap even more restrictions on genetic research. I believe genetics is mankind’s potentially greatest tool, if only we use it wisely.  It’s very overwhelming all the good and bad this one medicine could do. Everyone would have liked Einstein to live for a hundred plus years in age, but no one wants Saddam Hussein to live any longer than he must. Unfortunately, this medicine provides good and bad all in one. It’s just another dilemma for the world to deal with. <P>
